–Deceased","ABT 1272":"about 1272","1302":"1302","ABT 1302":"about 1302","Abt 1302":"about 1302","1272":"1272","1293":"1293","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Roger\"","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]},{"name":"Ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Loving’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert \" Roger\" Ap EMEROD was born about 1272. He had at least 5 sons with Gwerful Ferch HYWEL CAERLLION."},"et":{"ABT 1272–":"umbes 1272–Surnud","1272–Female":"1272–Surnud","1302–Male":"1302–Surnud","–1293":"–1293","–Male":"Surnud","1272–Male":"1272–Surnud","ABT 1272":"umbes 1272","1302":"1302","ABT 1302":"umbes 1302","Abt 1302":"umbes 1302","1272":"1272","1293":"1293"},"fi":{"ABT 1272–":"noin 1272–Kuollut","1272–Female":"1272–Kuollut","1302–Male":"1302–Kuollut","–1293":"–1293","–Male":"Kuollut","1272–Male":"1272–Kuollut","ABT 1272":"noin 1272","1302":"1302","ABT 1302":"noin 1302","Abt 1302":"noin 1302","1272":"1272","1293":"1293"},"fr":{"ABT 1272–":"environ 1272–Décédé","1272–Female":"1272–Décédée","1302–Male":"1302–Décédé","–1293":"–1293","–Male":"Décédé","1272–Male":"1272–Décédé","ABT 1272":"environ 1272","1302":"1302","ABT 1302":"environ 1302","Abt 1302":"environ 1302","1272":"1272","1293":"1293","lifeSummary":"Robert \" Roger\" Ap EMEROD est né environ 1272. Il a eu au moins 5 fils avec Gwerful Ferch HYWEL CAERLLION."},"de":{"ABT 1272–":"um 1272–Verstorben","1272–Female":"1272–Verstorben","1302–Male":"1302–Verstorben","–1293":"–1293","–Male":"Verstorben","1272–Male":"1272–Verstorben","ABT 1272":"um 1272","1302":"1302","ABT 1302":"um 1302","Abt 1302":"um 1302","1272":"1272","1293":"1293","lifeSummary":"Robert \" Roger\" Ap EMEROD wurde um 1272 geboren. Er hatte mit Gwerful Ferch HYWEL CAERLLION mindestens 5 Söhne."},"ht":{"ABT 1272–":"about 1272–Desede","1272–Female":"1272–Desede","1302–Male":"1302–Desede","–1293":"–1293","–Male":"Desede","1272–Male":"1272–Desede","ABT 1272":"about 1272","1302":"1302","ABT 1302":"about 1302","Abt 1302":"about 1302","1272":"1272","1293":"1293"},"hu":{"AB